<font color="#FF0000">THANKS FOR THE QUESTIONS LIEN</font><br>
<tt>Sat Apr 19 17:01:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Kim Phuc was one of many Vietnamese children whose futures were changed by war. I hate to see that picture because while it probably helped to end the war, it also was a violation of her privacy by the media. <br><br>
 It would be natural to be bitter.  Yet, here she was  at the Vietnam Veteran's Memorial Wall forgiving the pilot whose plane had dropped the napalm that fateful day.  I do not know that I could have done what she did and with such grace and dignity.  I only stand back and wonder how a person can forgive so much.  We have alot to learn from Phuc who continues to live each day with physical pain from the napalm.   <br><br>
I wished that her forgiveness would shame those in America who still hold bitterness toward the service personnel who served in South Vietnam into also forgiving and moving on.  Unfortunately I doubt that her presence made much of an impact except on the men and women who served in or with the Armed Forces.  It is extremely ironic that those who were physically and emotionally injured by our involvement in the war are more willing to forgive than our fellow citizens.  She, former North Vietnamese soldiers, and those who lost loved ones in that war shows us how far we have to go in forgiving ourselves for our involvement. <br><br>
You said the local newscast was distinctly resentful.  Not having seen the local broadcast,  I don't understand in what way it was resentful.   Is it possible they just didn't know how to respond?  When we are at a loss for words, frequently we mumble platitudes, or standard phrases to make ourselves feel better such as &quot;at least she is still alive.&quot;<br><br>
You asked if Vietnam is a bad memory, what are we.  You have me thinking of things that I have not thought on before.  I will offer my considered opinion,  I am putting my neck on the chopping block here because I know that there are many who will not agree with me.  Only you and others who settled in this country can confirm or deny  whether my truth is yours.   I speak of &quot;you&quot; but not specifically of &quot;Lien.&quot;  I know I may be guilty of over-generalization but what I have to say is the truth from my perspective.   You are people I came to know in Vietnam.  Some of you fought alongside us (or should I say our soldiers fought, alongside you for this was your country and ultimately your fight).  Some of you were our children born out of lust or love and  rejected in your own country.  Others worked for us as hootchmaid, etc. and thus became associated with Americans as enemies of the North.     The presence of your people willingly, even if  reluctantly leaving your  homeland  is proof that this war was not solely a foreign invented war.    You are the lucky ones (or are you?) that escaped the reeducation camps in your own country.  Today only you can answer what are you?  Are you reluctant refugees who would return home to Vietnam in a heartbeat if you could do so without fear of retribution, or Americans fully integrated into our society who would like to go back to Vietnam to visit family<br>
but have made this country your home. <br><br>
I know you don't want to deal with Dr. Spatz right now.  But, he has given you a gift of honesty  instead of hiding behind what he thinks you might like to hear and for him he has been most thoughtful in his first post.  His generalities about living separate from American society may not even apply to you who were an infant when Saigon fell in 1975. We know nothing about whether you came to the United States with family or alone (Because your parents were dead or they let you go to have a better life in the United States.  The families that adopted children from Vietnam's operation baby lift were thrilled to get you).  But, Dr. Spatz is telling the truth from a historical perspective that each new wave of immigrants has had to deal with making a place for themselves in the USA.   There still is value in listening to what  he has said if you believe in knowing why people who differ from you believe the way they do.  <br><br>
You mentioned that you are doing work on Vietnamese remembering practices about the war.  I for one would like to be able to read a draft or finished work.<br><br>
TO BARRY SPATZ:  You've gone over the edge with your last post.   Get a grip man.
<p><code>-- (decline to state)  (Betty) </code><p>


